>
  <p>This section provides practical tools and resources for navigating between Brazilian and European Portuguese. Whether you're a learner deciding which variant to study, a translator converting content between variants, or a professional communicating across Lusophone contexts, these resources offer concrete assistance.</p>

  <p>The tools complement our <a href="/portuguese-variants/">Overview</a>, <a href="/portuguese-variants/technical-deep-dive/">Technical analysis</a>, and <a href="/portuguese-variants/ontology/">Knowledge base</a> by providing interactive functionality. For guidance on applying these tools effectively, see our <a href="/portuguese-variants/challenges/">Common Challenges & Solutions</a> section.</p>

  <h2>Interactive Tools</h2>

  <h3>Vocabulary Translator</h3>

  <p>Our <a href="/portuguese-variants/tools/vocabulary-translator/">Vocabulary Translator</a> converts words between Brazilian and European Portuguese variants. Enter a term in one variant, and the tool provides the equivalent in the other variant, with notes on register, frequency, and context.</p>

  <p><strong>Example conversions:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>BR <em>ônibus</em> ↔ EP <em>autocarro</em> (bus)</li>
    <li>BR <em>celular</em> ↔ EP <em>telemóvel</em> (cell phone)</li>
    <li>BR <em>sorvete</em> ↔ EP <em>gelado</em> (ice cream)</li>
    <li>BR <em>banheiro</em> ↔ EP <em>casa de banho</em> (bathroom)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The translator includes over 500 common vocabulary divergences across categories including transportation, technology, food, housing, and daily life.</p>

  <h3>Progressive Tense Converter</h3>

  <p>The <a href="/portuguese-variants/tools/progressive-converter/">Progressive Tense Converter</a> transforms sentences between the Brazilian gerund construction (<em>estou falando</em>) and the European infinitive construction (<em>estou a falar</em>).</p>

  <p>This tool is particularly useful for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Translators adapting content between variants</li>
    <li>Learners practicing both constructions</li>
    <li>Content creators targeting specific markets</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Text Variant Analyzer</h3>

  <p>The <a href="/portuguese-variants/tools/text-analyzer/">Text Variant Analyzer</a> examines Portuguese text and identifies features suggesting Brazilian or European origin. The analyzer detects:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Vocabulary preferences (e.g., <em>ônibus</em> vs. <em>autocarro</em>)</li>
    <li>Progressive tense constructions</li>
    <li>Clitic pronoun placement patterns</li>
    <li>Possessive adjective position</li>
    <li>Second-person pronoun usage</li>
  </ul>

  <p>While not definitive—skilled writers can produce text in either variant regardless of origin—the analyzer provides useful indicators for understanding text characteristics.</p>

